MOST IMPORTANT ISSUES What's this?

We found the following problems in this heap dump.
For each problem where possible we report overhead: how much memory you would save
(in Kbytes and as a percentage of used memory) if you get rid of this problem.

Problem: High percentage of memory is used by instances of some class(es).
Details

Instances of some class(es) take up a big percentage of memory.
That can happen when the number of instances is very high, or their size
is very large (e.g. for arrays). Depending on whether all these instances
are really necessary or not, and also whether they are live or garbage,
this may or may not be a problem. See other report sections for more details
about these objects.

Problem: High percentage of memory retained by one or more GC roots, or memory leak.
Details

Some GC root(s) retain a large percentage of memory, and/or there are signs of a memory leak.
When one GC root holds most of the objects, it may be by design, or it may signal that
more objects than expected are accumulated in memory. Alternatively, when a single object,
typically a collection or array, references a very large number of other objects, AND they
take up a lot of memory, it may signal a memory leak. However, we cannot say for sure
that you have a real problem here. You need to inspect carefully the object trees in the
report section below and check whether they match your expectations.
For general discussion of this problem, see this article.

Problem: Memory is wasted by duplicate strings.  Overhead 5.7%  ( 513Kb ) 
Details

There are multiple String instances with the same value, like "yes", "yes", "no", "no", "no".
String duplication often occurs when, for example, an app reads the same common word
such as "yes" from the DB repeatedly, creating a new String instance every time.
See the report section below for concrete findings and suggestions how to fix.
For general discussion of this problem, see this article.

For full details, go to


Problem: Memory is wasted by bad (underutilized or otherwise suboptimal) collections.  Overhead 4.7%  ( 419Kb ) 
Details

There are some collections, such as j.u.HashMap and j.u.ArrayList, with high overhead per element.
Each collection needs memory for its implementation objects, which can be many.
When a collection contains no elements (empty), all its memory is wasted completely.
Consider creating such collections lazily. When a collection contains one or two elements,
you may in some situations store these elements in a more economical data structure,
such as an array, or at least make sure that you create the collection with the correct
(small) capacity. Otherwise, the memory used by the collection itself vs its payload is
disproportionally high. See the report section below for concrete findings and suggestions
on how to fix.
For general discussion of this problem, see this article.

For full details, go to


Problem: Memory is wasted by bad (underutilized or otherwise suboptimal) object arrays.  Overhead 4.1%  ( 371Kb ) 
Details

There are some object arrays, such as java.nio.ByteBuffer[] and Object[], with high overhead per element.
Each object array has a fixed-size internal, JVM-managed header, with most common
size of 16 bytes in HotSpot JVM and 12 bytes in Android. Each array slot,
whether it points to an object or is null, takes memory as well (4 bytes is most common).
Thus an empty array (with all elements null) wastes all its memory. Consider creating such
arrays lazily. When an array contains just one or two objects, you may in some situations
be able to store these elements more economically, e.g. as data fields in the enclosing class,
or at least make sure you create the array with the correct (small) size. Otherwise, the
memory used by the array internals vs its payload is disproportionally high. See the report
section below for concrete findings.

For full details, go to


Problem: Memory is wasted by primitive arrays with many zeroes and/or other problems.  Overhead 11.6%  ( 1,039Kb ) 
Details

There are some primitive arrays, such as byte[] and char[], with high overhead per element.
Each primitive array has a fixed-size internal, JVM-managed header, with most common
size of 16 bytes in HotSpot JVM and 12 bytes in Android. Each array slot takes
memory as well. Thus an empty array (with all elements equal to 0) wastes all its memory.
Consider creating such arrays lazily. Another common problem is underutilized buffers:
arrays where less than a half of the capacity is ever used. See if such buffers can be
allocated with more appropriate capacity. When an array contains just one or two elements,
you may in some situations be able to store these elements more economically, e.g. as
data fields in the enclosing class, or at least make sure you create the array with the
correct (small) size. Otherwise, the memory used by the array internals vs its payload is
disproportionally high. See the report section below for concrete findings.

Problem: Memory is wasted by duplicate primitive arrays.  Overhead 12.7%  ( 1,137Kb ) 
Details

There are some duplicate primitive arrays, such as byte[] and char[].
That is, there are multiple arrays with the same elements in the same order.
Duplication of primitive arrays often occurs when, for example, an app reads
the same frequently used piece of data, such as an image, from the DB repeatedly,
creating a new Java array for it every time. See the report section below for
concrete findings.
For general discussion of this problem, see this article.

Problem: High amount of off-heap memory allocated via java.nio.DirectByteBuffer objects.  Overhead 1584.3%  ( 141,863Kb ) 
Details

A considerable off-heap memory is allocated and retained by java.nio.DirectByteBuffer
objects in this app. Depending on whether all these buffers are really necessary or not,
and also whether they are live or garbage, this may or may not be a problem. Note that
a garbage (unreachable) DirectByteBuffer Java object still retains off-heap memory.
That memory area is released only when the GC gets to this Java object and wipes it out.
Sometimes that takes a lot of time. See the report section below for concrete findings.

8. Duplicate Strings.  Overhead 5.7%  ( 513Kb )  What's this?

  Total strings  ⓘ   Unique strings  ⓘ   Duplicate values  ⓘ  Overhead  ⓘ 
 28,217 19,642 3,794513Kb (5.7%)

What can I do to fix Duplicate Strings?


Of these duplicate strings, 57Kb, or 0.6% of used heap, are garbage.
This is a small amount, so you most likely don't need to worry about these strings.

The overhead (waste) of all 28,217 duplicate strings is 513Kb, or 5.7% of used heap.
That's how much memory you could save if all your string values were unique,
i.e. all problematic strings were de-duplicated, for example using the String.intern() call.

Duplicate strings wasting 93Kb, or 1.0% of used heap are referenced by collections or arrays:
  {j.u.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap}.keys (1,230 strings, waste 53Kb, or 0.6% of used heap)
    ↖jdk.internal.loader.ClassLoaders$AppClassLoader.parallelLockMap
  {j.u.Hashtable}.keys (480 strings, waste 22Kb, or 0.2% of used heap)
    ↖com.jprofiler.agent.triggers.nanoxml.XMLElement.attributes
  {j.u.Hashtable}.values (391 strings, waste 18Kb, or 0.2% of used heap)
    ↖com.jprofiler.agent.triggers.nanoxml.XMLElement.attributes

How to fix?

These strings may or may not be easy to de-duplicate.
In some situations, it may be possible to replace a constructor line like
  this.strList = strList;
with
  for (int i = 0; i < strList.size(); i++)
    strList.set(i, strList.get(i).intern());
  this.strList = strList;

However, this may not always be enough. E.g. if strings are added to strList in other methods,
you will need to add String.intern() there as well.

How to fix?

Such strings may be hard to de-duplicate.
You will need to check the code of the respective JDK classes to understand how they
initialize and manage the strings in internal collections.
Depending on how these internals work, you may be able to pass deduplicated strings
to these classes, or use reflection to deduplicate these strings in place.
Check this article for more information

How to fix?

Such strings may be hard to de-duplicate.
You may need to use reflection to intern strings managed by some JDK classes.
Check this article for more information



Duplicate strings wasting 10Kb, or 0.1% of used heap are referenced directly by other objects.
  com.jprofiler.agent.triggers.nanoxml.XMLElement.name (227 strings, waste 10Kb, or 0.1% of used heap)

How to fix?

Such strings are usually easy to de-duplicate. Often all you need is insert a String.intern() call in the constructor.
E.g. replace a line like
  this.name = name;
with
  this.name = name.intern();

However, check whether name is updated in other methods.
If so, you will need to add name.intern() there as well.



Note: the overhead from the sources reported above (264Kb, or 3.0% of used heap)

What can I do to fix Bad Collections?


The overhead (waste) of all 4,834 bad collections is 419Kb, or 4.7% of used heap.
That's how much memory you could save if:
- There were no empty collections
- There were no collections with just 1..4 elements
- There were no collections with big capacity and small size (sparse)

Some or all of the collections referenced by the data structures below are empty or contain 1..4 elements or sparse.
These collections waste 103Kb, or 1.2% of used heap. However, they are managed by JDK classes.

How to fix?

Bad collections managed by JDK classes are hard to fix, because you cannot modify
the code that creates and updates them. You will need to check the code of the respective
JDK classes to understand its inner workings. In some cases, it may be possible to use
reflection to access or modify the problematic collections.



Some of the collections referenced by the data structures below are either empty or contain just 1..4 elements each.
They waste 53Kb, or 0.6% of used heap. Can they be initialized lazily and with appropriate capacity?
  com.jprofiler.agent.triggers.nanoxml.XMLElement.attributes : reference 224 of bad j.u.Hashtable , waste 33Kb, or 0.4% of used heap
  com.jprofiler.agent.triggers.nanoxml.XMLElement.children : reference 233 of bad j.u.Vector , waste 20Kb, or 0.2% of used heap

How to fix?

Some of the collections above are either empty or contain just 1..4 elements (or key-value pairs).
Such collections are wasteful. Their internal implementation consumes memory
(sometimes hundreds of bytes per collection), but it's either not used at all (in empty collections)
or not fully amortized (in small-size collections). Furthermore, if a collection backed by array
is allocated with default capacity, such as 10 for ArrayList or 16 for HashMap,
the unused backing array slots containing nulls waste memory as well.
For example, you may have a class such as:
  class Foo {
    Map map = new HashMap<>(); // Allocated with default capacity 16
    void addToMap(K key, V val) { map.put(key, val); }
    ...
  }
but addToMap() is either never called or called just a few times for each Foo instance.

To address the problem, you should initialize these collections lazily and with small capacity, e.g.
  void addToMap(K key, V val) {
    if (map == null) map = new HashMap<>(2); // Init with capacity 2
    map.put(key, val);
  }



Note: the overhead from the sources reported above (156Kb, or 1.7% of used heap)
and the total overhead of all bad collections (419Kb, or 4.7% of used heap) don't match,
because there are 252 more of other data structures (not shown above),
each of which points to a small number of bad collections, and wastes less than 0.1% of used heap.
